*** (Cfront-3) ***

As noted in the headers of several files, the shared code
is proprietary and should be considered NON-FREE. Back in
1994 (the last version, 3.03), the copyright holder was
AT&T. Ever since then , the code has basically been abandonware.
It would be great if the current copyright holder could be
tracked down so that they could release the code under a free
license.

My interpretation is that the claude.ai cpp --> c translated
(rewritten) files still fall under this copyright. There
is currently an active debate about AI "license washing"
but my interpretation is the careful one.


*** Cfront-C4 ***

In anticipation of a future open source release of cfront-3,
I make sure that my changes are as permissively licensed as
possible. This would normally mean public domain, but this is
not universally recognized so I am instead opting for the
BSD0 license below.

